<br>
But I wanted to add one thing:  while there are plenty of couples out there looking to adopt a <!--EZCODE BOLD START--><strong>healthy, white newborn</strong><!--EZCODE BOLD END--> with a documented family medical history, there are few families who are looking to take in a child of a minority with a drug problem.  White babies draw premiums for adoption agencies;  black ones do not. . . and many of them wind up in foster care for most of their infancy, at which point - regardless of color - they are less likely to ever be placed in a permanent home.<br>
<br>
Recently, I saw John Irving speak at the UNLV Barrick Lecture series.  He spoke of his research in preparing to write _The Cider House Rules_ and said that, in reviewing files from orphanages from the early part of the last century, he would find pictures of the same children growing older, year by year.  So few of them were ever adopted.  The legalization of abortion in the country coincides with the extinction of the American orphanage.  It is naive to think the number of adoptions in the country would increase to absorb the number of unwanted children if Roe v. Wade were overturned.<br>
<br>
