<br>
Please elaborate on the following from earlier posts in this discussion:<br>
<br>
If it's &quot;fair&quot; for the woman to &quot;accept the consequences&quot; of her actions, what are the consequences for the man who also chose to have unprotected sex? Is he not every single bit as culpable as she is? Why or why not (and please don't say &quot;God didn't make him to carry babies&quot; because there are a lot of atheists and agnostics here who won't buy that. And if you're talking about US law then it fails the SOCAS test.)<br>
<br>
To be fair, perhaps the man should be made to wear one of those lead pregnancy bellies for 9 months, buy a whole new wardrobe to accommodate it, at the end of the 9 month he must push a cinderblock out of his naval for 18 hours (and if he can't do it, they'll cut it out with a knife). Then he must take 6 unpaid weeks off of work to recover. Oh, and he immediately becomes someone's unpaid personal body servant for 18 years and if he is ever neglectful or abusive he can go to jail. <br>
<br>
Also, what about the burdon of proof for whether it WAS rape? One of our correspondents here told us her devastating story of rape. I guess you did not read it, (I hope you didn't just conveniently ignore it because it didn't fit your argument).  Had she been impregnated, how could she have proven it was rape and should she have had to prove it? Do you really want to add to the burdens of women who are raped by making them go to court, etc. before they can terminate? But if you don't make them go to court, any pregnant woman could claim she was raped, right? So how do you handle it?<br>
<br>
You also said the consequence (being forced to carry an unwanted pregnancy to term) is for &quot;unprotected sex.&quot; But what about birth control failure? It happens all the time - in fact, abstinence is the only 100% effective method of birth control. So you have a woman who did &quot;practice safe sex&quot; but is pregnant just the same. Why do you still feel the need to punish her with &quot;consequences&quot; that she will face the rest of her life?<br>
